{"_id":"dd318ee9-89cd-310a-bdf9-83836217e409","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"28dde5772b48c92e08b8050411aa5ba8","message":"If you cannot use asynchronous methods, then (by definition) you need to block the thread. So, blocking via GetAwaiter().GetResult() is the best you can do.\r\n\r\nNote that no other thread is created; it's just blocking the current thread. However, since you *have* to block a thread anyway (because you can't use async), then that solution is the best you can do.","postId":"2012_07_dont-block-on-async-code-abe2d9c7-c3e9-3ed8-827c-021686fa2310","replyTo":"317e0731-4504-325c-b71e-f4650a74f0f5","date":"2017-10-04T15:43:28Z","timestamp":1507131808,"authorUserId":"disqus:stephen_cleary"}